{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"226de82a-7cde-4a69-be8d-539a01cbb1ac","content":"The best approach for a .NET 8 app in a K8s pod is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already in the container)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips for K8s specifically:**\n\n- Copy the trace out with `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`\n- If you can't install tools in the image, use a [sidecar or ephemeral debug container](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-an-ephemeral-container)\n- For lower overhead in production, consider `--profile cpu-sampling` (default 10ms interval) rather than `--profile gc-collect`\n\n**Alternative — `perf` (native + managed stacks):**\n\nIf you need OS-level context (kernel, native interop):\n\n```bash\nperf record -g -p <PID> -- sleep 30\nperf script > out.stacks\n```\n\nBut `dotnet-trace` is usually simpler and sufficient for managed code hot paths.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3e0b1839-733c-4985-9d24-22ce2f0e7acc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostics question - I can answer from knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":443,"requestId":"CA5F:3B57F0:1E563B5:217A4CA:6A0525EE"},"id":"61b476fc-6fe4-408b-8a8b-1944b668822c","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:31:37.141Z","parentId":"c515ae61-4633-43b5-bae1-72f2dbdac796"}
